Note: ================================================================
Note: Verilog Emitter - Complete Translation Orchestration
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_lexer.runa" as VerilogLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_parser.runa" as VerilogParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_to_hir.runa" as VerilogToHIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/verilog/hir_to_verilog.runa" as HIRToVerilog
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore

@Reasoning:
Verilog uses a full pipeline orchestrator rather than the simple
byte-buffer emitter pattern of other backends because Verilog supports
round-trip translation (Verilog -> HIR -> Verilog). The emitter owns
the lexer, parser, AST/HIR translator, backend, and the lists of
errors/warnings produced at each pipeline stage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
72-byte heap-allocated struct: source_file (offset 0), lexer (8),
parser (16), translator (24), backend (32), ast (40), hir (48), errors
list (56), warnings list (64). All sub-objects are allocated lazily as
the pipeline progresses and remain owned by the emitter for the
duration of its life.
@End Implementation

Type called "VerilogEmitter":
    source_file as String
    lexer as Integer
    parser as Integer
    translator as Integer
    backend as Integer
    ast as Integer
    hir as Integer
    errors as Integer
    warnings as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Allocates a clean emitter with empty error/warning lists; the lexer,
parser, translator, backend, AST, and HIR slots are filled in as the
pipeline runs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 72 bytes, zeroes the pointer slots (offsets 8 through 48),
then creates fresh List instances for errors (offset 56) and warnings
(offset 64). The source_file slot at offset 0 is initialized to the
empty string.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Two list allocations plus one heap allocation per emitter. Cheap relative
to the cost of running the pipeline.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "create_emitter" that takes nothing returns Integer:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 72
    proc write_string from Memory with emitter_ptr, 0, ""
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 24, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 32, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 40, 0
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 48, 0
    Let errors be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56, errors
    Let warnings be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 64, warnings
    Return emitter_ptr
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-arg internal form lets the round_trip helper reuse a single
emitter across both legs of a round trip without paying for two emitter
allocations or losing the error/warning lists between stages.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Runs lex -> parse -> translate. After each stage, calls merge_errors to
fold per-stage errors into the emitter's error list. If any stage
reports errors, returns 0 immediately so the caller can short-circuit
without continuing into an undefined state. On success, returns the
HIR root pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Cold path - called once per source file. Three full pipeline stages
dominate the cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Treats verilog_source as untrusted input; all parse errors are funneled
through the lexer/parser/translator error lists and propagated to the
emitter via merge_errors, never crashing the orchestrator.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "verilog_to_hir_with_emitter" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, verilog_source as String returns Integer:
    Note: Multi-arg internal form. Runs the Verilog -> HIR pipeline through a
    Note: caller-supplied emitter. The single-arg `verilog_to_hir` wrapper
    Note: below is what the central dispatcher in translation.runa calls.
    proc write_string from Memory with emitter_ptr, 0, verilog_source

    Let lexer_ptr be proc create_lexer from VerilogLexer
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 8, lexer_ptr

    Let tokens be proc scan from VerilogLexer with lexer_ptr, verilog_source

    Let lexer_errors be proc get_errors from VerilogLexer with lexer_ptr
    Let error_count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with lexer_errors
    If error_count is greater than 0:
        proc merge_errors with emitter_ptr, lexer_errors
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser_ptr be proc create_parser from VerilogParser with tokens
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 16, parser_ptr

    Let ast be proc parse from VerilogParser with parser_ptr
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 40, ast

    Let parser_errors be proc get_errors from VerilogParser with parser_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with parser_errors
    If error_count is greater than 0:
        proc merge_errors with emitter_ptr, parser_errors
        Return 0
    End If

    Let translator_ptr be proc create_translator from VerilogToHIR
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 24, translator_ptr

    Let hir be proc translate from VerilogToHIR with translator_ptr, ast
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 48, hir

    Let translator_errors be proc get_errors from VerilogToHIR with translator_ptr
    Set error_count to proc get_list_size from ListCore with translator_errors
    If error_count is greater than 0:
        proc merge_errors with emitter_ptr, translator_errors
        Return 0
    End If

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-arg internal form for the backend leg of the pipeline. Used by
round_trip so it can reuse an existing emitter (and any errors already
collected) instead of creating a new one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Stores the HIR module at offset 48, creates the HIR->Verilog backend at
offset 32, invokes its translate method, and returns the generated
Verilog source. Backend errors (if any) would be merged through the
backend's own mechanism in future revisions; currently the backend is
expected to produce output for any valid HIR.
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_verilog_with_emitter" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Note: Multi-arg internal form. Runs the HIR -> Verilog pipeline through a
    Note: caller-supplied emitter. The single-arg `hir_to_verilog` wrapper
    Note: below is what the central dispatcher in translation.runa calls.
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 48, hir_module

    Let backend_ptr be proc create_backend from HIRToVerilog
    proc write_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 32, backend_ptr

    Let verilog_output be proc translate from HIRToVerilog with backend_ptr, hir_module

    Return verilog_output
End Process

@Reasoning:
End-to-end test entry point: ingest Verilog source, lower to HIR, then
regenerate Verilog source from that HIR. Used by golden-output tests
to verify round-trip fidelity. Empty string on the forward leg failure
prevents the caller from feeding partial/null HIR into the backend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Chains verilog_to_hir_with_emitter then hir_to_verilog_with_emitter,
reusing the same emitter so any forward-leg errors are captured. If the
forward leg returned 0 (failure), returns the empty string without
attempting regeneration.
@End Implementation

Process called "round_trip" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, verilog_source as String returns String:
    Let hir be proc verilog_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, verilog_source

    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If

    Let regenerated be proc hir_to_verilog_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, hir

    Return regenerated
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Dispatcher Entry Points - Single-Arg Wrappers
Note: ================================================================
Note: The central dispatcher in translation.runa calls the orchestrator by
Note: the canonical single-arg shape. These wrappers create a fresh emitter,
Note: run the pipeline, and return the result so the dispatcher does not
Note: need to manage emitter lifecycles.

@Reasoning:
Single-arg dispatcher entry point matching the convention enforced by
translation.runa: every frontend exposes a one-argument `X_to_hir`
function. This wrapper hides emitter lifecycle from the dispatcher.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh emitter and forwards to verilog_to_hir_with_emitter.
The emitter is not destroyed here so callers can still inspect errors;
the orchestrator's lifetime is tied to its containing arena.
@End Implementation

Process called "verilog_to_hir" that takes verilog_source as String returns Integer:
    Note: Single-arg dispatcher entry point. Creates a fresh emitter, runs
    Note: the Verilog -> HIR pipeline, and returns the HIR root pointer or 0
    Note: on failure.
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc verilog_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, verilog_source
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-arg dispatcher entry point matching the convention enforced by
translation.runa: every backend exposes a one-argument `hir_to_X`
function.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a fresh emitter and forwards to hir_to_verilog_with_emitter.
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_verilog" that takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Note: Single-arg dispatcher entry point. Creates a fresh emitter, runs
    Note: the HIR -> Verilog pipeline, and returns the generated Verilog
    Note: source or the empty string on failure.
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc hir_to_verilog_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Stage helpers (lexer, parser, translator) own their own error lists;
when one stage produces errors, the orchestrator must hoist them into
the emitter's central error list so callers can inspect a unified view.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the emitter's error list pointer (offset 56), then iterates the
incoming error_list by index, appending each error to the emitter's
list. Returns 1 unconditionally because the underlying list append
cannot fail in the current List implementation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the size of the incoming error list. Called at most three times
per pipeline run (after lex, parse, translate).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "merge_errors" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer, error_list as Integer returns Integer:
    Let errors be proc read_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with error_list
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than count:
        Let error be proc get_from_list from ListCore with error_list, index
        proc add_to_list from ListCore with errors, error
        Set index to index plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the unified error list so callers (golden-output tests, the
driver) can format diagnostics in a single place.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_errors" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc read_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56
End Process

@Reasoning:
Boolean shorthand asking "did the pipeline produce any errors". Lets
callers gate on success/failure without computing the list size twice.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the error list pointer, asks the List its size, returns 1 if
positive else 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "has_errors" that takes emitter_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let errors be proc read_integer from Memory with emitter_ptr, 56
    Let count be proc get_list_size from ListCore with errors
    If count is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Alias used by older call sites that say "translate" rather than
"verilog_to_hir"; preserved for source compatibility.
@End Reasoning

Process called "translate_from_verilog" that takes verilog_source as String returns Integer:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc verilog_to_hir_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, verilog_source
End Process

@Reasoning:
Alias used by older call sites that say "translate" rather than
"hir_to_verilog"; preserved for source compatibility.
@End Reasoning

Process called "translate_to_verilog" that takes hir_module as Integer returns String:
    Let emitter_ptr be proc create_emitter
    Return proc hir_to_verilog_with_emitter with emitter_ptr, hir_module
End Process
